instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.A1286: What is A1286? A1286 is a model number for a 15 inch size MacBook Pro Unibody from years Late 2008, Mid 2009, Mid 2009 , Mid 2010, Early 2011, Late 2011, Mid 2012 with EMC 2255, that may contain one of these boards depending on the year & configuration: 820-2330, 820-2532, 820-2523, 820-2533, 820-2850, 820-2915, 820-3330..
definitions.820-2850: What is 820-2850? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.C9560: What is C9560? Tantalum capacitor on 820-2850 logic board that often dies and causes intermittent power to framebuffer PP1V8R1V55_S0GPU_ISNS and PP1V8R1V55_S0GPU_ISNS_R rail, causing GPU kernel panics. Replace with non-tantalum if machine is having random black screen or kernel panics.

threads.title: [SOLVED]<MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1286</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> crashing on program start up to restart
threads.message:
[COLOR=#231F20][FONT=Helvetica][SIZE=14px]Hi guys,
fixed a water damaged computer for a customer seemed to be working before i sent it back out but the customer told me its was crashing to the your mac restarted from an error screen. i asked him to do a pram reset and after he said "The pram helped a little but i had to end up reinstalling mac os x. I also did disk repair. It fixed some applications starting up but chrome makes the mac restart sometimes. Even opening finder may make it crash"  

Any ideas? i was thinking ram maybe? i have a new set i am going to try on it when he brings it back in. Just trying to get any idea of what it might be or where to look before he brings it back in.  
thanks in advance 
Nate[/SIZE][/FONT][/COLOR]

threads.title: [SOLVED]<MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER>A1286</MACBOOK MODEL NUMBER> crashing on program start up to restart
threads.message: Did you replace it with the same capacitor or a normal sized one? To be clear, if you are using a tiny tantalum cap like the one that was there, you missed duke's advice. The capacitor Apple installs for <CAPACITOR>C9560</CAPACITOR> is not suitable for this application. If you did not have to modify the board or use a jumper to fit the cap you placed, you didn't use the right cap. The cap you put there should be a 330UF that is bigger than the one that was there; not tantalum. Like this. [url]http://www.mouser.com/Search/ProductDetail.aspx?R=EEF-LX0D331R4virtualkey66720000virtualkey667-EEF-LX0D331R4[/url]
